Rating: 3
Very good! Made an excellent accompaniment to the recipe for Shredded Collard Greens and Pickled Apples on this site. A couple quick notes: * Yes, you'll need more than 1.5 minutes per side to cook the latkes. More like 3.5. Plan accordingly. * I subbed a finely chopped scallion for the fresh chives, as I had one on hand -- yum! * Quick tip: if your arm feels like it's going to fall off while you're grating the parsnips, try just using a vegetable peeler to shave lots of narrow strips. Then use your chef's knife or mezzaluna to chop them fine. The resulting coarse texture is inauthentic, but it gets the thumb's up from me. * If you've never made latkes before, you can absolutely make them ahead of your main course and keep them warm in the oven while you prepare the rest of your meal. They stay crisp! Cross my heart! :)

Rating: 4
Excellent recipe, but definitely not like your grandma's latkes. Our family typically grated about half of the potato with the extra fine side of the grater, giving the latkes more of a pancake texture and less of a hash brown consistency that these latkes turned out to have. But for what these are, they are excellent. Word of caution -- if you let the batter sit for an hour or two, you will probably need to add a little more flour, as a lot of liquid will drain off of them.

